    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_176475020" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/176475020" />
    <a title="Jim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1895570-jim"><img alt="Jim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1484874117p2/1895570.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/176475020?book_show_action=true">Jun 13, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jim" href="/user/show/1895570-jim">Jim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1895570-jim?shelf=france">france</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1895570-jim?shelf=20th-century-lit">20th-century-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer176475020" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3657394230204248266">In this, the fourth of Francois Mauriac&apos;s that I have read, I am just now beginning to see what he is about. <b>The Knot of Vipers</b> of the title is not only a description of the unnamed miser&apos;s heart, but also of his family, which is conspiring to subvert his will and take as much of his fortune for themselves. <br/><br/>Except for the last few pages, the story is narrated by the miser, who, at the age of sixty-eight, is suffering from angina and appears to be in danger of imminent heart failure. The aridity </span>
  <span id="freeText3657394230204248266" style="display:none">In this, the fourth of Francois Mauriac's that I have read, I am just now beginning to see what he is about. <b>The Knot of Vipers</b> of the title is not only a description of the unnamed miser's heart, but also of his family, which is conspiring to subvert his will and take as much of his fortune for themselves. <br /><br />Except for the last few pages, the story is narrated by the miser, who, at the age of sixty-eight, is suffering from angina and appears to be in danger of imminent heart failure. The aridity of his last years, as he sees his wife, children, and grandchildren turn into adversaries begins to take a heavy toll on him. When, after he takes a trip to Paris, his wife dies suddenly in Bordeaux, the miser relents. It is almost like the end of Dickens's <b>Christmas Carol</b>, except that this Scrooge does not live happily ever after. At the end of his life, the very end, he wins through to an epiphany which he is prevented from expressing to us.<br /><br />Mauriac's world is a world without grace. Money and family hatred seem to be omnipresent. And that Scroogelike reversal in the last act rings false:<blockquote>Even the genuinely good cannot, unaided, learn to love. To penetrate beyond the absurdities, the vices, and, above all, the stupidities of human creatures, one must possess the secret of a love which the world has now forgotten. Until that secret shall have been discovered, all betterment in conditions of life will be in vain.</blockquote>There is something of the Jansenist in Mauriac, which is echoed in subsequent writers like Georges Bernanos (in <b>Diary of a Country Priest</b> and <b>Mouchette</b>) and filmmakers like Robert Bresson (who filmed both of the Bernanos novels named). Instead of handing shoveling pious thoughts into our head, Mauriac and his followers want us to turn toward God -- if for no other reason than that a life without God seems so bleak.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3657394230204248266" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

