    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3428275863" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3428275863" />
    <a title="Monty Milne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14797192-monty-milne"><img alt="Monty Milne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1363450934p2/14797192.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3428275863?book_show_action=true">Jul 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Monty Milne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Monty Milne" href="/user/show/14797192-monty-milne">Monty Milne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3428275863" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15610720494273094599">This is a novel of great psychological depth and artful construction. Despite being concerned with the journal of an embittered, hate filled old man, it is completely absorbing and compelling. There are some surprising twists and turns and some lapidary vignettes of minor characters. Given the author’s Catholicism we are I think intended to read this as a novel about the operation of Divine Grace, but I like the way things are left unsettlingly ambiguous and other interpretations are left open.<br/><br/>T</span>
  <span id="freeText15610720494273094599" style="display:none">This is a novel of great psychological depth and artful construction. Despite being concerned with the journal of an embittered, hate filled old man, it is completely absorbing and compelling. There are some surprising twists and turns and some lapidary vignettes of minor characters. Given the author’s Catholicism we are I think intended to read this as a novel about the operation of Divine Grace, but I like the way things are left unsettlingly ambiguous and other interpretations are left open.<br /><br />There is something peculiarly French about the anti-clericalism of the central character. Most English people of my generation think of the Church of England, if they think of it at all, with amused or affectionate indifference. But Monsieur Louis is the kind of person who hates Catholicism so much he must always eat a cutlet on Good Friday, rather than the “haricot beans and sardines in oil” of his pious family. To me, this kind of thing feels slightly mad – I bet plenty of Anglican bishops tuck into microwaved cutlets on Good Friday and don’t give it a second thought. But of course for a French Roman Catholic it is – or perhaps was – a signifier of so much more. <br /><br />One does not have to share the philosophy or religion of the author (and I certainly don’t) to feel moved and stirred by this beautifully crafted tale. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15610720494273094599" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


