<div id="review_1005712623" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1005712623" />
    <a title="Elliot A" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27139785-elliot-a"><img alt="Elliot A" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1587678579p2/27139785.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1005712623?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elliot A" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elliot A" href="/user/show/27139785-elliot-a">Elliot A</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27139785-elliot-a?shelf=classic-literature">classic-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1005712623" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13978105587241365636">I read this story years ago and it took me about just as long to remember its name; however, I never forgot the impact it had on me. As part of the reading list for a religious studies course focusing on love and friendship, this story was meant to help the students examine the deterioration of a person&apos;s heart and soul.<br/><br/>Throughout the entire story the reader is kept in suspension between completely hating the main character and finding themselves cheering him on during his revelations and letter</span>
  <span id="freeText13978105587241365636" style="display:none">I read this story years ago and it took me about just as long to remember its name; however, I never forgot the impact it had on me. As part of the reading list for a religious studies course focusing on love and friendship, this story was meant to help the students examine the deterioration of a person's heart and soul.<br /><br />Throughout the entire story the reader is kept in suspension between completely hating the main character and finding themselves cheering him on during his revelations and letter writing.<br /><br />The author does a fantastic job in keeping the reader on the edge of their seat (I was actually reading the book while cooking dinner, because I refused to put it down) by creating a character that had such depth and was so multidimensional that it was almost impossible to ascertain the true nature of the main character's personality. <br /><br />Layers upon layers of human and personality psychology are added and then slowly examined.<br /><br />This book is definitely not a light or quick read, but I would recommend it to anyone, who is interested in psychology addressed and discussed through the creation of a fictional character.<br /><br /><a href="http://www.elliotscribbles.com" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">ElliotScribbles</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="13978105587241365636" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


