<div id="review_175309874" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/175309874" />
    <a title="eva" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/210336-eva"><img alt="eva" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1587410696p2/210336.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/175309874?book_show_action=true">Jun 09, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="eva" class="user" itemprop="url" name="eva" href="/user/show/210336-eva">eva</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/210336-eva?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/210336-eva?shelf=bookclub-jerrys">bookclub-jerrys</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer175309874" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9173060861884440140">all right, all right. it took two rounds of voting to settle on the april book club selection, and i specifically voted against this one for no good reason both times. but i ended up loving it. mauriac doesn&apos;t shy away from making the main character a truly wretched, hateful old man, and demonstrating in surgical detail just how responsible he is for his own misery. at the same time, you can&apos;t get away from feeling compassion for his very human vulnerabilities, misunderstandings, and failures. i</span>
  <span id="freeText9173060861884440140" style="display:none">all right, all right. it took two rounds of voting to settle on the april book club selection, and i specifically voted against this one for no good reason both times. but i ended up loving it. mauriac doesn't shy away from making the main character a truly wretched, hateful old man, and demonstrating in surgical detail just how responsible he is for his own misery. at the same time, you can't get away from feeling compassion for his very human vulnerabilities, misunderstandings, and failures. i was heartbroken by the subtle portrayal of how people can live entwined together for decades without ever developing more than a sliver of understanding between each other. i also appreciated how deftly mauriac handles the religious aspects of the story - it's obvious that they're a deep part of his intent, and he treats them with a multilayered slyness and sincerity all the way through to the dramatic conclusion.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9173060861884440140" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


