<div id="review_1247687183" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1247687183" />
    <a title="Audrey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5436039-audrey"><img alt="Audrey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1397520421p2/5436039.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1247687183?book_show_action=true">Apr 06, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Audrey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Audrey" href="/user/show/5436039-audrey">Audrey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5436039-audrey?shelf=read-for-school">read-for-school</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5436039-audrey?shelf=listens">listens</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5436039-audrey?shelf=europe">europe</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5436039-audrey?shelf=catholic-fiction">catholic-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5436039-audrey?shelf=catholic">catholic</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer1247687183&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1247687183" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12930187715109119637">This is a perceptively written story about a miserable, broken man reflecting back on his life. Caught in the web of radical self-sufficiency, greed, and bitter pride, Louis has nearly succeeded in blocking out all joy. <br/><br/>Far from being a preachy or feel-good story, <i>Vipers’ Tangle</i> is a honestly reflective—and often uncomfortable—novel that is unafraid to confront the horrible realities and consequences of sin. Louis is a convincing character that reveals universal aspects of human struggle. Initia</span>
  <span id="freeText12930187715109119637" style="display:none">This is a perceptively written story about a miserable, broken man reflecting back on his life. Caught in the web of radical self-sufficiency, greed, and bitter pride, Louis has nearly succeeded in blocking out all joy. <br /><br />Far from being a preachy or feel-good story, <i>Vipers’ Tangle</i> is a honestly reflective—and often uncomfortable—novel that is unafraid to confront the horrible realities and consequences of sin. Louis is a convincing character that reveals universal aspects of human struggle. Initially so callous as to seem thoroughly unlikable, one gradually begins to pity and even empathize with the hardened spirit of this very unhappy man. As the title states, his raw self-awareness discloses a prisoner trapped in a miserable tangle of vices. <br /><br />Throughout the novel, Louis’s evolution as a character is subtle and organic. In many ways, he comes to believe in God because he has tried doing everything on his own and sees how completely that failed him. As Louis fights and rants, relaying how everyone has been so wretched to him, he comes to realize that the source of rot is his own surly blend of inner snakes, threatening to devour him and robbing him of the peace that is only found outside of himself. Through his grasping and pulling from God, Louis is only more sharply reminded of the desolate "mud" of his own life … and how in need he is of a Savior.<br /><br />Human relationships are a key force throughout the story, and Mauriac stresses how each person’s actions affect so many others. The novel is set up in a way that shows the dangers of merely blaming others instead of taking a sober look at oneself. As John Donne so memorably put it, “no man is an island, entire of itself; every man is a piece of the continent, a part of the main.” In the same way, there is no such thing as a private sin. Each omission or rejection of the good affects someone else. For example, even at the end of the novel, it is apparent that Louis’s children have been negatively influenced by the vices of their father.<br /><br />While hypocrisy and false piety are major targets of Mauriac’s, he also shows how God often chooses to touch our lives through authentic encounters with individuals. Although Louis feels repulsion at the thought of sacrificing himself, he is still attracted to the compelling goodness and virtue in characters such as Marie and Luc. Through their witnesses, he senses an unseen but palpable life that draws him chiefly because it is so opposite to his own brokenness. In this way, he discovers that evil, while temporarily alluring, is nothing compared to the quiet joy of divine grace, which eventually floods and illuminates even the dark recesses of his embittered soul. <br /><br />This isn’t a fun read, but it is a valuable one. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12930187715109119637" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


