<div id="review_1128295622" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1128295622" />
    <a title="Andrei" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27769221-andrei"><img alt="Andrei" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1128295622?book_show_action=true">Dec 10, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Andrei" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Andrei" href="/user/show/27769221-andrei">Andrei</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27769221-andrei?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27769221-andrei?shelf=exquisite">exquisite</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer1128295622&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1128295622" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10846287693463934661">This book perfects, IMHO, what the author started with &quot;There Desqueryeux&quot;. The viper&apos;s tangle is a metaphor for the rigid society and for the human soul sometimes. The novel is narrated from the first person&apos;s point of view and slowly depicts an dying man&apos;s life, guiding the reader to penetrate this mysterious character that can be easily mistaken. What I liked the most was how the author sketches his main character, swinging between the miser burgher who marries a noble woman, thus penetrating</span>
  <span id="freeText10846287693463934661" style="display:none">This book perfects, IMHO, what the author started with "There Desqueryeux". The viper's tangle is a metaphor for the rigid society and for the human soul sometimes. The novel is narrated from the first person's point of view and slowly depicts an dying man's life, guiding the reader to penetrate this mysterious character that can be easily mistaken. What I liked the most was how the author sketches his main character, swinging between the miser burgher who marries a noble woman, thus penetrating the high society and the loving, delicate on the inside man who still loves his wife after almost 50 years of marriage. By acknowledging his fondness for money, he surpasses his condition and finally admits that love was always a stronger force in his life, against all odds.<br />He writes a diary, only to be read by his soul mate, sensing that he is about to die shortly. Maybe it's just me who sees that, but as well as I read through, he starts by expressing his intense hate for his wife and all his relatives and sometimes loses intensity as he progresses with his diary, ending up with mixed feelings. He is, nonetheless a ruthless father who seeks innovative ways to prevent his children to inherit his fortune, only to see his efforts baffled in the end. Again, maybe it's just me wanting to see the good man inside, but after his wife dies before him, thus ruining his plans, he finds his diary useless and his hate without a subject. A secret alchemy of feelings makes me glimpse a completely opposed person that struggles to become the good father everyone wishes for. Unfortunately for me, who secretly wanted a happy ending, his offspring are toady and tasteless and maybe don't really deserve to spend all that money, except for a single one.<br />This guy is somehow obsessed with justice, being a lawyer himself, and really seeks someone who has enough substance to earn his inheritance. Is that to blame? Of course, good books don't give an answer straight away and also don't necessarily have happy endings.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10846287693463934661" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


