        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1358076110" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11046341698228835297">Like the three star rating says &quot;I liked it&quot;.<br/>Here&apos;s a short overview of my feelings during the reading of this book, but first, a short explanation on what it&apos;s about.<br/>It&apos;s about an old man getting his vengeance on his wife. He writes an account of their life (from HIS point of view, bien sur!) and his main goal is to leave this letter for the wife to find after he is dead (in order to avoid having to deal with wiveys reactions, duh). So he tells about his life growing up and how they meet and ho</span>
  <span id="freeText11046341698228835297" style="display:none">Like the three star rating says "I liked it".<br />Here's a short overview of my feelings during the reading of this book, but first, a short explanation on what it's about.<br />It's about an old man getting his vengeance on his wife. He writes an account of their life (from HIS point of view, bien sur!) and his main goal is to leave this letter for the wife to find after he is dead (in order to avoid having to deal with wiveys reactions, duh). So he tells about his life growing up and how they meet and how he starts his work as a lawyer and then their kids and so on. He also writes about what is happening at present since he is old and his kids are very aware of his days being pretty much counted for.<br />What I felt during the reading:<br />1. Firstly a great big GET OVER IT, MAN! His vengeance is all based on something that happened years ago and never got over. He never moved on. What a baby.<br />2. He's one to talk with what he's been like to her.<br />3. Wow, didn't see that one coming.<br />4. At the very end I felt: I knew it all along, but needed Mauriac to tell me.</span>
